<br>
Respectfully, but the difference is that black people and gay people are not very real enemies of white people. They are not engaged in bitter, documented, violent struggle with white people. <br>
<br>
A better analogy would be Israelis and Palestinians. I'm sure that some Palestinians know some wonderful Israelis who they trust and love, and vice versa. However, you could not blame an Israeli for being fearful of spending too much time around Palestinian folks, since any one of them could have designs on destroying the Israeli people. Likewise, you cannot expect Palestinians, in general, to welcome each and every Israeli into their arms openly, given that some Palestinian families have been torn apart by Israeli aggression. (Please understand I am not taking sides here, nor am I making a judgment call on who the aggressors/aggressees are; I'm just trying to make a point.)<br>
<br>
In Norrath, there are established *wars* going on, and it's realistic to roleplay that you at least have some knowledge of those things, even if you choose to ignore them and accept each individual on a person by person basis, like Pixxii does.<br>
<br>
Though I respectfully disagree with some of the more hardline sentiments about sticking to the old alignment structures, I also understand why characters who roleplay good vs. evil do so. Just like I would understand why Palestinians or Israelis might have justified distrust toward each other and I would *not* consider them racist in that distrust, I don't consider those who roleplay good vs. evil as racist for doing so, as they, based on EQ history, have justification for that distrust.<br>
<br>
